s Angeles Dodgers]], [[Boston Red Sox]], and [[Houston Astros]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=grosski01 |title=Kip Gross Stats\n |publisher=Baseball Almanac |accessdate=December 3, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Nik Ingersoll|Nik Ingers\u00f6ll]], American entrepreneur and designer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wgbh.org/news/2017/10/06/local-news/forbes-under-30-summit-brings-inspiration-boston-schools|title=Forbes Under 30 Summit Brings Inspiration To Boston Schools|date=2017-10-06|website=News|language=en|access-date=2019-06-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.starherald.com/news/local_news/former-scottsbluff-man-named-to-forbes-under-list/article_21fc6757-86d5-5ad5-bc00-19b00fb56dca.html|title=Former Scottsbluff man named to Forbes' '30 Under 30' list|last=Report|first=Star-Herald Staff|website=starherald.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-28}}</ref>\n* [[Galen B. Jackman]], [[U.S. Army]] [[Major general#United States|major general]] (retired), [[Nancy Reagan]]'s escort throughout the [[death and state funeral of Ronald Reagan|state funeral proceedings]] of former U.S. President [[Ronald Reagan]], first commanding general of [[Joint Force Headquarters National Capital Region]]\n* [[Jacqueline Logan]], silent film actress spent her childhood in Scottsbluff.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Even a Movie Star Can't Always Get an Airplane|last=|first=|date=|work=Morning World-Herald|access-date=|publication-place=Omaha|publication-date=March 19, 1926}}</ref>\n* [[Vic Marker]], three-time Midwest Golden Glove boxer, who beat Archie Moore in the Golden Glove Finals in the late 1930s.\n* [[Randy Meisner]], former bassist of the rock band the [[Eagles (band)|Eagles]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/artists/randy-meisner/biography/|title=Randy Meisner Bio {{!}} Randy Meisner Career|website=CMT Artists|access-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Teresa Scanlan]], Miss America 2011 (graduated from Scottsbluff High School)<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.missamerica.org/our-miss-americas/2010/2011.aspx|title = Miss America : 2011|website = www.missamerica.org|access-date = March 4, 2016|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160305085012/http://www.missamerica.org/our-miss-americas/2010/2011.aspx|archivedate = March 5, 2016|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n*Maggie Bennett, a fictional character on Netflix's [[The Ranch (TV series)|The Ranch]] is from Scottsbluff and her father worked in the sugar factory.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Scotts Bluff County, Nebraska}}\n{{Nebraska}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1900 establishments in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Cities in Scotts Bluff County, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Cities in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1900]]\n[[Category:Scottsbluff Micropolitan Statistical Area]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Scottsbluff, Nebraska\n|native_name              = \n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = 2010-1101-19-ScottsbluffNE.jpg\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = Aerial view of Scottsbluff\n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = Scotts_Bluff_County_Nebraska_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Scottsbluff_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Scottsbluff, Nebraska\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n<!-- Location -->\n| subdivision_type = Country\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Nebraska]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Nebraska|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Scotts Bluff County, Nebraska|Scotts Bluff]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = Mayor\n|leader_name              = Raymond Gonzales\n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|leader_title2            = \n|leader_name2             = \n|established_title        = Founded\n|established_date         = 1900\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_31.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jan 12, 2019}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 17.14\n|area_land_km2            = 17.02\n|area_water_km2           = 0.12\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 6.62\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 6.57\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.04\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 14733\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"wwwcensusgov\"/>\n|population_total         = 15039\n|population_density_km2   = 873.75\n|population_density_sq_mi = 2262.89\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[Mountain Time Zone|Mountain (MST)]]\n| utc_offset = &minus;7\n|timezone_DST             = MDT\n| utc_offset_DST = &minus;6\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 1186\n|elevation_ft             = 3891\n|coordinates              = {{coord|41|52|2|N|103|39|39|W|region:US-NE_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]s\n|postal_code              = 69361, 69363\n|area_code                = [[Area code 308|308]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 31-44245\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0833318<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=January 31, 2008|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=October 25, 2007}}</ref>\n|website                  = [http://www.scottsbluff.org/ www.scottsbluff.org]\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n}}\n\n'''Scottsbluff''' is a city in [[Scotts Bluff County, Nebraska|Scotts Bluff County]], in the western part of the state of [[Nebraska]], in the [[Great Plains]] region of the United States. The population was 15,039 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. Scottsbluff is the largest city in the [[Nebraska Panhandle]], and the [[List of cities in Nebraska|13th largest city]] in [[Nebraska]].\n\nScottsbluff was founded in 1899 across the [[North Platte River]] from its namesake, a bluff that is now a [[United States National Park|U.S. National Park]] called [[Scotts Bluff National Monument]]. The monument was named after [[Hiram Scott]] (1805\u20131828), a fur trader with the [[Rocky Mountain Fur Company]] who was found dead in the vicinity on the return trip from a fur expedition. The smaller town of [[Gering, Nebraska|Gering]] had been founded south of the river in 1887. The two cities have since grown together to form the 7th largest urban area (the [[Scottsbluff Micropolitan Statistical Area]]) in Nebraska.\n\n==History==\nScottsbluff was laid out in 1899 when the railroad was extended to that point.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.casde.unl.edu/history/counties/scottsbluff/scottsbluff-gering/ | title=The Twin Cities: Gering and Scottsbluff | publisher=University of Nebraska | work=Center for Advanced Land Management Information Technologies | accessdate=August 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Other names==\nIn the [[Lakota language]], Scottsbluff is called ''p\u021fa\u014bk\u00e9ska wakp\u00e1 ot\u021f\u00fa\u014bwahe'' (\"[[Platte River]] City\", lit. \"[[abalone]] river city\").<ref>{{cite book |last=Ullrich |first=Jan F. |title=New Lakota Dictionary |url=http://www.lakotadictionary.org/nldo.php |edition=2nd |year=2014 |publisher=Lakota Language Consortium |location=Bloomington, IN |isbn=978-0-9761082-9-0}}</ref>\n\n==Geography and climate==\nScottsbluff is located at {{Coord|41|52|2|N|103|39|39|W|type:city}} (41.867140, \u2212103.660709).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=April 23, 2011|date=February 12, 2011|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|6.27|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|6.22|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|0.05|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=June 24, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112090031/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=January 12, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nScottsbluff has a [[semi-arid climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''[[Semi-arid climate#Cold Semi-arid climates|''BSk'']]''), with wide seasonal and day-to-day variation as well as a large [[diurnal temperature variation]], and is located in [[Hardiness zone|USDA Plant Hardiness Zone]] 5a.<ref>{{cite web|title=USDA Plant Hardiness Zone Map|url=http://planthardiness.ars.usda.gov/PHZMWeb/|publisher=United States Department of Agriculture |accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> Summers are hot, and winters dry and cold, though [[chinook wind]]s can loosen the cold's grip, often bringing temperatures above {{convert|50|\u00b0F}}. The monthly daily average temperature ranges from {{convert|26.1|\u00b0F|1}} in December to {{convert|74.1|\u00b0F|1}} in July.<ref name=\"NOWData Cheyenne, WY\"/>  Over the course of a year, there is an average 5.3&nbsp;days with maxima {{convert|100|\u00b0F|0}} or above, 45&nbsp;days with maxima reaching at least {{convert|90|\u00b0F|0}}, 29&nbsp;days with a maximum at or below the freezing mark, and 13&nbsp;days with minima at or below {{convert|0|\u00b0F|0}}.<ref name=\"NOWData Cheyenne, WY\"/>\n\nExtremes in temperature have ranged from {{convert|110|\u00b0F|0}} on July 11, 1939, down to {{convert|\u221245|\u00b0F|0}} on [[Great Blizzard of 1899|12 February 1899]]. The year 1989 saw temperatures as extreme as {{convert|109|\u00b0F|0}} and {{convert|\u221242|\u00b0F|0}},<ref name = ThreadEx/> whilst the month of February 1962 saw temperatures as hot as {{convert|77|\u00b0F}} on the 11th and as cold as {{convert|\u221228|\u00b0F}} on the 28th.<ref name=\"NOWData Cheyenne, WY\">{{cite web |publisher=[[National Weather Service]], Cheyenne, Wyoming |url=http://w2.weather.gov/climate/xmacis.php?wfo=cys |title=NOW Data \u2013 NOAA Online Weather Data |accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrecipitation is heavily concentrated in the spring and summer months, with only May and June averaging over {{convert|2|in|mm|1|disp=or}}. The wettest single day has been June 7, 1953, with {{convert|3.18|in|mm|1|disp=or}} of rain, whilst the wettest calendar month on record has been June 1947 with {{convert|8.33|in|mm|1}} and the wettest calendar year 1915 with {{convert|27.48|in|mm|1}}. The months of November 1939 and March 2012 did not see even a trace of precipitation, whilst nineteen other months since 1893 have seen only a trace. The driest calendar year has been 2012 with {{convert|6.99|in|mm|1}}.<ref name=\"NOWData Cheyenne, WY\"/> Snow typically falls in light amounts, with a 1981\u22122010 seasonal average of {{convert|42.1|in|m|2|disp=or}}; the most snow in one month has been {{convert|31.3|in|m|2}} in October 2009, and the greatest depth of snow on the ground {{convert|23|in|m|2|disp=or}} on April 14, 1927. The most snowfall in a season is {{convert|81.9|in|m|2|disp=or}} between July 2009 and June 2010; the least snow being {{convert|13.5|in|m|2|disp=or}} between July 1933 and June 1934.<ref name=\"NOWData Cheyenne, WY\"/>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Scottsbluff, Nebraska (1981\u20132010 normals, extremes 1893\u2013present)\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F =  74\n|Feb record high F =  77\n|Mar record high F =  87\n|Apr record high F =  93\n|May record high F = 103\n|Jun record high F = 106\n|Jul record high F = 110\n|Aug record high F = 106\n|Sep record high F = 102\n|Oct record high F =  93\n|Nov record high F =  80\n|Dec record high F =  77\n\n|Jan avg record high F =  61.9\n|Feb avg record high F =  65.8\n|Mar avg record high F =  74.9\n|Apr avg record high F =  82.8\n|May avg record high F =  91.2\n|Jun avg record high F =  97.8\n|Jul avg record high F = 102.3\n|Aug avg record high F =  99.6\n|Sep avg record high F =  94.5\n|Oct avg record high F =  84.9\n|Nov avg record high F =  73.1\n|Dec avg record high F =  61.6\n|year avg record high F= 102.7\n|Jan high F = 40.8\n|Feb high F = 44.4\n|Mar high F = 52.7\n|Apr high F = 61.4\n|May high F = 71.6\n|Jun high F = 82.1\n|Jul high F = 89.8\n|Aug high F = 87.7\n|Sep high F = 77.9\n|Oct high F = 64.1\n|Nov high F = 50.2\n|Dec high F = 39.6\n|year high F= 63.6\n|Jan low F = 13.7\n|Feb low F = 16.3\n|Mar low F = 23.8\n|Apr low F = 31.9\n|May low F = 42.9\n|Jun low F = 52.3\n|Jul low F = 58.3\n|Aug low F = 56.2\n|Sep low F = 45.4\n|Oct low F = 32.9\n|Nov low F = 21.5\n|Dec low F = 12.5\n|year low F= 34.1\n|Jan avg record low F = &minus;8.5\n|Feb avg record low F = &minus;6.2\n|Mar avg record low F =  6.8\n|Apr avg record low F = 16.7\n|May avg record low F = 28.0\n|Jun avg record low F = 39.7\n|Jul avg record low F = 49.6\n|Aug avg record low F = 47.1\n|Sep avg record low F = 30.6\n|Oct avg record low F = 16.7\n|Nov avg record low F =  2.7\n|Dec avg record low F = &minus;10.6\n|year avg record low F= &minus;18.8\n|Jan 