13 Bronze \u2013 Best Reusable Swim Nappy\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Baby & Children\u2019s Reader Favourite Awards 2018 \u2013 2<sup>nd</sup> Place Winner \u2013 Diaper & Baby Wipes\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Junior Design Awards 2018 \u2013 Bronze \u2013 Best Children\u2019s Swim Collection\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Made for Mums Awards 2018 \u2013 Gold \u2013 Reusable Nappy\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Made for Mums Awards 2018 \u2013 Silver \u2013 Everyday Parenting Essential\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Made for Mums Awards 2018 \u2013 Silver \u2013 Hero Health Product for Mums\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Mother & Baby Awards 2017 \u2013 Bronze \u2013 Best Reusable Nappy \n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n*Pollock, Claire & Silvester, Liz, ''Kids Superbrands'' (2006)\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[https://www.bambinomio.com/ Bambino Mio Website]\n*[http://www.nappyalliance.co.uk/ The Nappy Alliance]\n\n[[Category:Companies established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Clothing companies of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Woodsedits", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAwards:updated format", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bambino_Mio"}
{"title_page": "Beoley", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|official_name = Beoley\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.324|-1.906|display=inline,title}}\n|os_grid_reference = SP0669\n|london_distance = {{convert|95|mi|km}}\n|label_position = left\n|population = 945\n|population_ref = (parish, including [[Holt End]]) ([[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 census]])<ref name=ONS>{{cite web |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do;jsessionid=ac1f930d30d57cfd8b24c17c4286acb58b72f3eae571?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790553&nsjs=true&nsck=true&nssvg=true&nswid=1020 |title=Area selected: Bromsgrove (Non-Metropolitan District) |author= |date= |work=Neighbourhood Statistics: Full Dataset View |publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]] |accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref>\n|static_image_name = St Leonards Church, Beoley.jpg\n|static_image_caption = St Leonard's parish church\n|civil_parish = Beoley\n|shire_district = [[Bromsgrove (district)|Bromsgrove]]\n|shire_county = [[Worcestershire]]\n|region = West Midlands\n|country = England\n|constituency_westminster = [[Bromsgrove (UK Parliament constituency)|Bromsgrove]]\n|postcode_district = B98\n|postcode_area = B\n|post_town = [[Redditch]]\n|dial_code = 01527\n|website =\n}}\n\n'''Beoley''' is a small village and larger [[Civil parishes in England|civil parish]]<ref name=\"ordnancesurvey\">{{cite web |url=http://data.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/doc/7000000000003094.html |title=Beoley |publisher=[[Ordnance Survey]] |date=19 July 2013 |accessdate=22 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://moderngovwebpublic.bromsgrove.gov.uk/mgConvert2PDF.aspx?ID=3108 |publisher=Bromsgrove District Council |title=Bromsgrove District and West Mercia Police Parish Boundaries|accessdate=22 February 2014|date=2008}}</ref> just north of [[Redditch]] in the [[Bromsgrove (district)|Bromsgrove District]] of [[Worcestershire]], and adjoins [[Warwickshire]] to the east. The [[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 census]] gave a parish population of 945,<ref name=ONS/> most living at [[Holt End]]. The parish includes the hamlet of Portway adjacent to the A435 road, and adjoins Redditch's populous northern suburb of [[Church Hill, Worcestershire|Church Hill]],<ref name=\"extent\">{{cite web |url=http://data.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/doc/geometry/3094-125 |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20140724181752/http%3A//data.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/doc/geometry/3094%2D125 |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 July 2014 |title=Extent of Beoley Civil Parish |publisher=Ordnance Survey |accessdate=22 February 2014 }}</ref> and the civil parishes of [[Alvechurch]], [[Tanworth-in-Arden]], [[Mappleborough Green]] and [[Wythall]].<ref name=\"ordnancesurvey\"/>\n\n==Manor==\nThe estates of the [[Order of Saint Benedict|Benedictine]] [[Pershore Abbey]] included lands at ''Beoleahe'' from at least the 10th century when [[Edgar the Peaceful]] restored them to the monks in AD 972.<ref name=Willis-Bund>{{harvnb|Willis-Bund|Page|1924|pp=12\u201319}}</ref> The [[Domesday Book]] of 1086 records that the abbey held 21 [[Hide (unit)|hides]] of land at ''Beolege'' and [[Yardley, Birmingham|Yardley]].<ref name=Willis-Bund/> The de Beauchamp family of [[Elmley Castle]], ancestors of [[William de Beauchamp, 9th Earl of Warwick]], were [[mesne lord]]s of the manor from the 12th century until about 1265, when they acquired the overlordship (superiority) from the abbey.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> In the 13th century the [[Toponymy|toponym]] was variously rendered ''Boleye'', ''Beleg'' or ''Buley''.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> The superiority of Beoley descended with the de Beauchamps until the death of [[Henry de Beauchamp, 1st Duke of Warwick]] in 1446, when it passed to his daughter Elizabeth, wife of [[George Nevill, 1st Baron Latimer]].<ref name=Willis-Bund/> This superiority is said to have remained with the Latimers until [[John Nevill, 4th Baron Latimer]] sold it in 1549.<ref name=Willis-Bund/>\n\nWilliam Sheldon of Abberton, however, must have held a good part of the parish by feu as he was established at Balford Hall in Beoley in the reign of Edward IV (1460-1483). In addition he bought Benyt\u2019s Place in that parish in 1488. Sheldon supported the [[Yorkists]] at the battle of [[Battle of Bosworth Field|Bosworth]] in 1485, and as a result of the definitive [[House of Lancaster|Lancastrian]] victory there he was deprived of his property, but it was restored to him before he died in 1517.<ref>Victoria County History, vol.iv, p.14, note 25.</ref> In his Inquisition Post Mortem, held at [[Pershore]], it was said that Sheldon owned Balford Hall and seven other houses and 460 acres of land in Beoley, and more elsewhere in [[Worcestershire]] and [[Warwickshire]]. In his will<ref>[[Prerogative Court of Canterbury]], 35 Holder</ref> he made bequests to the churches at Beoley and Abberton and to Pershore Abbey.\n\nSheldon was succeeded at Beoley by his son Ralph (d.1546), who was married to Philippa, daughter of Baldwin Heath of Ford Hall, Wootton Wawen.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> Ralph was imprisoned in the [[Marshalsea]] in 1580 for [[Recusant|recusancy]] but was released on medical grounds.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> Ralph was succeeded at Beoley by his eldest son, William (b.c1500-1570), who possessed the manors of Weston, Warwickshire, Abberton (jointly with his brother Francis), and, by now, virtually the entire parish of Beoley (some 4000 acres). He was Receiver at the Court of Augmentations, Knight of the Shire for Worcestershire, and Sheriff of the same county. Around 1534, William Sheldon purchased 2,000 acres of land at Skilts, between Beoley and his mother\u2019s home Ford Hall, which lands had been a grange of [[Studley Priory, Oxfordshire|Studley]] Priory. His magnificent tomb is in Beoley parish church.\n\nWilliam Sheldon was succeeded by his son, another Ralph Sheldon (1537-1613), who was married to Anne, daughter of Sir Robert Throgmorton, Knt., of Coughton, who had attended the reception of [[Anne of Cleves]]. A [[Roman Catholic]], Ralph Sheldon was a courtier at the Court of Queen Mary, and sometime a courier for [[Mary Queen of Scots]] between her place of confinement and Scotland. He is frequently mentioned in State Papers as a [[recusant]], and in 1594 there is reference to an alleged premeditated rebellion in North Wales, \"the chiefest aid for which is to come from Ralph Sheldon\", and that he had sent an emissary to Louvain \"with letters to Cardinal Allen.\" He is said to have been responsible for the construction of the great manor house at Weston Park in Warwickshire, another Sheldon estate in Long Compton parish. He was succeeded by his eldest son and heir Edward (1561-1643). Also a Royalist, in August 1636 King Charles 1st visited Warwick, and a day or two later went on \"to Weston at Mr. Sheldon's house with great delight.\"\n\nEdward's son and heir William Sheldon of Beoley (1589-1659), always resided at Weston Park (where he died). In 1611, he married Elizabeth, daughter of the recusant [[William Petre, 2nd Baron Petre]].<ref>Barnard,E.A.B., ''The Sheldons'', 1936, pg. 48</ref> Considered \"a man of literary taste\", Sheldon was a [[Cavalier|Royalist]] and at various times during the early years of the Civil War he was, in his turn, harassed as \"a Popish delinquent\".\n\nIn 1660 after the [[Restoration (England)|Restoration of the Monarchy]] Beoley was restored ''via'' Richard Sheldon to William's son, the famous [[antiquary]] Ralph Sheldon (1623-1684). He was married to Henrietta Maria, daughter of Thomas, 1st Viscount Savage, but had no issue.<ref name=Willis-Bund/><ref>Barnard, 1936, p.54-6.</ref> Beoley now passed to a first cousin once removed, Ralph Sheldon, Lord of Beoley & Weston (1653-1720) who was married to Mary Anne, daughter of John Elliot of Gatacre Park, Shropshire. His estates passed to his eldest son and heir, Edward (1679-1746) and then to his eldest son William (1715-1780). His son Ralph Sheldon inherited Beoley in 1780, but by 1788 it was said to be heavily mortgaged and he sold the manor to a Thomas Holmes.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> Holmes separated Beoley Hall (see below) and {{convert|300|acre|ha}} of land from the rest of the manor and sold off the two lots to separate buyers.<ref name=Willis-Bund/>\n\n==Beoley Hall==\nThe Sheldons' main [[manor house]] at Beoley was originally Balford Hall. In September 1643 William Sheldon's manor house at Weston Park was ransacked, and cattle and goods taken away by soldiers \"to a great value\". The following December his manor house at Beoley was burnt to the ground, all his goods and cattle \"plundered by the soldiers\". In 1648 the [[Roundhead|Parliamentarian]] authorities sequestrated Beoley.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> It was restored to the Sheldons in 1660 who had the present Beoley Hall built after the Restoration of the Monarchy, either late in the 17th<ref name=Pevsner81>{{harvnb|Pevsner|1968|p=81}}</ref> or early in the 18th century.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> It is a [[Neoclassical architecture|neoclassical]] house on an H-shaped plan, originally entirely three-storeyed, built of brick and entirely [[stucco]]ed.<ref name=Willis-Bund/>\n\nIn 1791 the new proprietor Thomas Holmes had the east wing rebuilt to plans by [[John Sanders (architect)|John Sanders]], with two storeys built to the same height as the original three and a [[portico]] with four [[Tuscan order|Tuscan]] columns.<ref name=Pevsner81/> On the south end of the east wing a bow window was added to the ground floor in 1791 and a matching window was subsequently added to the first floor above.<ref name=Pevsner81/> The main staircase is lit by a round skylight.<ref name=Pevsner81/>\n\nIn 1968 Beoley Hall was in poor condition<ref name=Pevsner81/> but since 1986 it has been a [[Categories of listed building|Grade II listed building]].<ref name=Listed>{{NHLE |num= 1296862 |desc=Beoley Hall |date=16 July 1986 |accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref> It is now divided into apartments.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-156119-beoley-hall-beoley |title=Beoley Hall, Beoley |author= |date= |work=British Listed Buildings |publisher=British Listed Buildings |accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Parish church==\nThe oldest parts of the [[Church of England parish church]] of [[Leonard of Noblac|Saint Leonard]]<ref>[http://www.stleonardsbeoley.org.uk/ St Leonard's Church]</ref> date from the early part of the 12th century<ref name=Willis-Bund/> and include the [[chancel]] arch.<ref name=Pevsner80>{{harvnb|Pevsner|1968|p=80}}</ref> The south [[Arcade (architecture)|arcade]] dates from the early or middle part of the 13th century and the north arcade from about 1300.<ref name=Pevsner80/> The west tower is a [[Perpendicular Gothic]]<ref name=Pevsner80/> addition from about 1400<ref name=Willis-Bund/> and the north aisle was also rebuilt in the Perpendicular style.<ref name=Pevsner80/>\n\nThe Sheldon Chapel on the north side was added for the recusant Ralph Sheldon in about 1580.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> Its stone altar is said to be a gift from [[Pope Gregory XIII]].<ref name=Willis-Bund/> The church was restored in 1885 and the Sheldon Chapel was restored in 1891.<ref name=Willis-Bund/>\n\nThe tower has a [[Change ringing|ring]] of eight bells.<ref name=DoveDetails>{{cite web |url= http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?searchString=Beoley&Submit=+Go+&DoveID=BEOLEY |last1=Dawson |first1=George |last2=Pickford |first2=Chris |last3=Denton |first3=Philip |title=Beoley S Leonard |work=[[Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers]] |publisher=[[Central Council of Church Bell Ringers]] |date=3 December 2011 |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref> The oldest is the tenor bell, cast in 1601 by [[Hugh Watts (bell-founder)|Hugh Watts]]<ref name=DoveDetails/> of [[Leicester]].<ref name=DoveFounders>{{cite web |url= http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/founders.php |title=Bell Founders |author=Dovemaster |work=[[Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers]] |publisher=[[Central Council of Church Bell Ringers]] |date=31 October 2012 |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref> The seventh bell was cast in 1611 by one of the Newcombe family of [[Bellfounding|bellfounders]] of Leicester. The fourth bell was cast in 1622 by Henry III Oldfield<ref name=DoveDetails/> of Nottingham.<ref name=DoveFounders/> Richard Sanders of [[Bromsgrove]]<ref name=DoveFounders/> cast the third bell in 1708<ref name=DoveDetails/> and the fifth bell in 1709.<ref name=DoveDetails/> John [[Rudhall of Gloucester]]<ref name=DoveFounders/> cast the seventh bell in 1789<ref name=DoveDetails/> which completed a ring of six.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> In 1999 this was increased to eight by the addition of new treble and second bells cast by [[Whitechapel Bell Foundry]].<ref name=DoveDetails/>\n\n==Amenities==\nThe civil parish of Beoley has two public houses: the ''Cross and Bowling Green'' at Branson's Cross,  and the ''Village Inn'' at Holt End.<ref>[http://www.villageinnbeoley.co.uk/ The Village Inn, Beoley] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124015434/http://www.villageinnbeoley.co.uk/ |date=24 November 2011 }}</ref> The village has a first school<ref>[http://www.beoleyfirst.com/documents/welcome.php Beoley First School] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707223930/http://www.beoleyfirst.com/documents/welcome.php |date=7 July 2011 }}</ref> and a village hall.<ref>[http://www.beoley.org.uk/ Beoley Village Hall] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122111557/http://www.beoley.org.uk/ |date=22 January 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Edward Sheldon (translator)|Edward Sheldon]] (1599\u20131687), translator of religious works from French.\n*[[Ralph Sheldon]] (1623\u20131694), [[Cavalier|Royalist]] and [[antiquary]], nephew of Edward.\n*[[Mary Whateley]] (1738\u20131835), poet and playwright who wrote as Harriett Airy and Mary Darwall (her married name).\n*[[Sarah Cooper (marmalade maker)|Sarah Cooper]] (1848\u20131932), (''n\u00e9e'' Gill), originator of [[Frank Cooper's]] Oxford marmalade.\n*[[Sarah Falkland (journalist)|Sarah Falkland]] (living), a relief news presenter for [[BBC Midlands Today]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book |last=Pevsner |first=Nikolaus |authorlink=Nikolaus Pevsner |series=[[The Buildings of England]] |title=Worcestershire |year=1968 |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |location=Harmondsworth |pages=80\u201381 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Willis-Bund |editor1-first=J.W. |editor1-link=John William Willis-Bund |editor2-last=Page |editor2-first=W.H. |editor2-link=William Henry Page |series=[[Victoria County History]] |title=A History of the County of Worcester: Volume 4 |year=1924 |location=London |publisher= |pages=12\u201319 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Commons category|Beoley}}\n\n{{Bromsgrove}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Worcestershire]]\n[[Category:Villages in Worcestershire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|official_name = Beoley\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.324|-1.906|display=inline,title}}\n|os_grid_reference = SP0669\n|london_distance = {{convert|95|mi|km}}\n|label_position = left\n|population = 945\n|population_ref = (parish, including [[Holt End]]) ([[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 census]])<ref name=ONS>{{cite web |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do;jsessionid=ac1f930d30d57cfd8b24c17c4286acb58b72f3eae571?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790553&nsjs=true&nsck=true&nssvg=true&nswid=1020 |title=Area selected: Bromsgrove (Non-Metropolitan District) |author= |date= |work=Neighbourhood Statistics: Full Dataset View |publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]] |accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref>\n|static_image_name = St Leonards Church, Beoley.jpg\n|static_image_caption = St Leonard's parish church\n|civil_parish = Beoley\n|shire_district = [[Bromsgrove (district)|Bromsgrove]]\n|shire_county = [[Worcestershire]]\n|region = West Midlands\n|country = England\n|constituency_westminster = [[Bromsgrove (UK Parliament constituency)|Bromsgrove]]\n|postcode_district = B98\n|postcode_area = B\n|post_town = [[Redditch]]\n|dial_code = 01527\n|website =\n}}\n\n'''Beoley''' is a small village and larger [[Civil parishes in England|civil parish]]<ref name=\"ordnancesurvey\">{{cite web |url=http://data.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/doc/7000000000003094.html |title=Beoley |publisher=[[Ordnance Survey]] |date=19 July 2013 |accessdate=22 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://moderngovwebpublic.bromsgrove.gov.uk/mgConvert2PDF.aspx?ID=3108 |publisher=Bromsgrove District Council |title=Bromsgrove District and West Mercia Police Parish Boundaries|accessdate=22 February 2014|date=2008}}</ref> just north of [[Redditch]] in the [[Bromsgrove (district)|Bromsgrove District]] of [[Worcestershire]], and adjoins [[Warwickshire]] to the east. The [[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 census]] gave a parish population of 945,<ref name=ONS/> most living at [[Holt End]]. The parish includes the hamlet of Portway adjacent to the A435 road, and adjoins Redditch's populous northern suburb of [[Church Hill, Worcestershire|Church Hill]],<ref name=\"extent\">{{cite web |url=http://data.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/doc/geometry/3094-125 |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20140724181752/http%3A//data.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/doc/geometry/3094%2D125 |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 July 2014 |title=Extent of Beoley Civil Parish |publisher=Ordnance Survey |accessdate=22 February 2014 }}</ref> and the civil parishes of [[Alvechurch]], [[Tanworth-in-Arden]], [[Mappleborough Green]] and [[Wythall]].<ref name=\"ordnancesurvey\"/>\n\n==Manor==\nThe estates of the [[Order of Saint Benedict|Benedictine]] [[Pershore Abbey]] included lands at ''Beoleahe'' from at least the 10th century when [[Edgar the Peaceful]] restored them to the monks in AD 972.<ref name=Willis-Bund>{{harvnb|Willis-Bund|Page|1924|pp=12\u201319}}</ref> The [[Domesday Book]] of 1086 records that the abbey held 21 [[Hide (unit)|hides]] of land at ''Beolege'' and [[Yardley, Birmingham|Yardley]].<ref name=Willis-Bund/> The de Beauchamp family of [[Elmley Castle]], ancestors of [[William de Beauchamp, 9th Earl of Warwick]], were [[mesne lord]]s of the manor from the 12th century until about 1265, when they acquired the overlordship (superiority) from the abbey.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> In the 13th century the [[Toponymy|toponym]] was variously rendered ''Boleye'', ''Beleg'' or ''Buley''.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> The superiority of Beoley descended with the de Beauchamps until the death of [[Henry de Beauchamp, 1st Duke of Warwick]] in 1446, when it passed to his daughter Elizabeth, wife of [[George Nevill, 1st Baron Latimer]].<ref name=Willis-Bund/> This superiority is said to have remained with the Latimers until [[John Nevill, 4th Baron Latimer]] sold it in 1549.<ref name=Willis-Bund/>\n\nWilliam Sheldon of Abberton, however, must have held a good part of the parish by feu as he was established at Balford Hall in Beoley in the reign of Edward IV (1460-1483). In addition he bought Benyt\u2019s Place in that parish in 1488. Sheldon supported the [[Yorkists]] at the battle of [[Battle of Bosworth Field|Bosworth]] in 1485, and as a result of the definitive [[House of Lancaster|Lancastrian]] victory there he was deprived of his property, but it was restored to him before he died in 1517.<ref>Victoria County History, vol.iv, p.14, note 25.</ref> In his Inquisition Post Mortem, held at [[Pershore]], it was said that Sheldon owned Balford Hall and seven other houses and 460 acres of land in Beoley, and more elsewhere in [[Worcestershire]] and [[Warwickshire]]. In his will<ref>[[Prerogative Court of Canterbury]], 35 Holder</ref> he made bequests to the churches at Beoley and Abberton and to Pershore Abbey.\n\nSheldon was succeeded at Beoley by his son Ralph (d.1546), who was married to Philippa, daughter of Baldwin Heath of Ford Hall, Wootton Wawen.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> Ralph was imprisoned in the [[Marshalsea]] in 1580 for [[Recusant|recusancy]] but was released on medical grounds.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> Ralph was succeeded at Beoley by his eldest son, William (b.c1500-1570), who possessed the manors of Weston, Warwickshire, Abberton (jointly with his brother Francis), and, by now, virtually the entire parish of Beoley (some 4000 acres). He was Receiver at the Court of Augmentations, Knight of the Shire for Worcestershire, and Sheriff of the same county. Around 1534, William Sheldon purchased 2,000 acres of land at Skilts, between Beoley and his mother\u2019s home Ford Hall, which lands had been a grange of [[Studley Priory, Oxfordshire|Studley]] Priory. His magnificent tomb is in Beoley parish church.\n\nWilliam Sheldon was succeeded by his son, another Ralph Sheldon (1537-1613), who was married to Anne, daughter of Sir Robert Throgmorton, Knt., of Coughton, who had attended the reception of [[Anne of Cleves]]. A [[Roman Catholic]], Ralph Sheldon was a courtier at the Court of Queen Mary, and sometime a courier for [[Mary Queen of Scots]] between her place of confinement and Scotland. He is frequently mentioned in State Papers as a [[recusant]], and in 1594 there is reference to an alleged premeditated rebellion in North Wales, \"the chiefest aid for which is to come from Ralph Sheldon\", and that he had sent an emissary to Louvain \"with letters to Cardinal Allen.\" He is said to have been responsible for the construction of the great manor house at Weston Park in Warwickshire, another Sheldon estate in Long Compton parish. He was succeeded by his eldest son and heir Edward (1561-1643). Also a Royalist, in August 1636 King Charles 1st visited Warwick, and a day or two later went on \"to Weston at Mr. Sheldon's house with great delight.\"\n\nEdward's son and heir William Sheldon of Beoley (1589-1659), always resided at Weston Park (where he died). In 1611, he married Elizabeth, daughter of the recusant [[William Petre, 2nd Baron Petre]].<ref>Barnard,E.A.B., ''The Sheldons'', 1936, pg. 48</ref> Considered \"a man of literary taste\", Sheldon was a [[Cavalier|Royalist]] and at various times during the early years of the Civil War he was, in his turn, harassed as \"a Popish delinquent\".\n\nIn 1660 after the [[Restoration (England)|Restoration of the Monarchy]] Beoley was restored ''via'' Richard Sheldon to William's son, the famous [[antiquary]] Ralph Sheldon (1623-1684). He was married to Henrietta Maria, daughter of Thomas, 1st Viscount Savage, but had no issue.<ref name=Willis-Bund/><ref>Barnard, 1936, p.54-6.</ref> Beoley now passed to a first cousin once removed, Ralph Sheldon, Lord of Beoley & Weston (1653-1720) who was married to Mary Anne, daughter of John Elliot of Gatacre Park, Shropshire. His estates passed to his eldest son and heir, Edward (1679-1746) and then to his eldest son William (1715-1780). His son Ralph Sheldon inherited Beoley in 1780, but by 1788 it was said to be heavily mortgaged and he sold the manor to a Thomas Holmes.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> Holmes separated Beoley Hall (see below) and {{convert|300|acre|ha}} of land from the rest of the manor and sold off the two lots to separate buyers.<ref name=Willis-Bund/>\n\n==Beoley Hall==\nThe Sheldons' main [[manor house]] at Beoley was originally Balford Hall. In September 1643 William Sheldon's manor house at Weston Park was ransacked, and cattle and goods taken away by soldiers \"to a great value\". The following December his manor house at Beoley was burnt to the ground, all his goods and cattle \"plundered by the soldiers\". In 1648 the [[Roundhead|Parliamentarian]] authorities sequestrated Beoley.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> It was restored to the Sheldons in 1660 who had the present Beoley Hall built after the Restoration of the Monarchy, either late in the 17th<ref name=Pevsner81>{{harvnb|Pevsner|1968|p=81}}</ref> or early in the 18th century.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> It is a [[Neoclassical architecture|neoclassical]] house on an H-shaped plan, originally entirely three-storeyed, built of brick and entirely [[stucco]]ed.<ref name=Willis-Bund/>\n\nIn 1791 the new proprietor Thomas Holmes had the east wing rebuilt to plans by [[John Sanders (architect)|John Sanders]], with two storeys built to the same height as the original three and a [[portico]] with four [[Tuscan order|Tuscan]] columns.<ref name=Pevsner81/> On the south end of the east wing a bow window was added to the ground floor in 1791 and a matching window was subsequently added to the first floor above.<ref name=Pevsner81/> The main staircase is lit by a round skylight.<ref name=Pevsner81/>\n\nIn 1968 Beoley Hall was in poor condition<ref name=Pevsner81/> but since 1986 it has been a [[Categories of listed building|Grade II listed building]].<ref name=Listed>{{NHLE |num= 1296862 |desc=Beoley Hall |date=16 July 1986 |accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref> It is now divided into apartments.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-156119-beoley-hall-beoley |title=Beoley Hall, Beoley |author= |date= |work=British Listed Buildings |publisher=British Listed Buildings |accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Parish church==\nThe oldest parts of the [[Church of England parish church]] of [[Leonard of Noblac|Saint Leonard]]<ref>[http://www.stleonardsbeoley.org.uk/ St Leonard's Church]</ref> date from the early part of the 12th century<ref name=Willis-Bund/> and include the [[chancel]] arch.<ref name=Pevsner80>{{harvnb|Pevsner|1968|p=80}}</ref> The south [[Arcade (architecture)|arcade]] dates from the early or middle part of the 13th century and the north arcade from about 1300.<ref name=Pevsner80/> The west tower is a [[Perpendicular Gothic]]<ref name=Pevsner80/> addition from about 1400<ref name=Willis-Bund/> and the north aisle was also rebuilt in the Perpendicular style.<ref name=Pevsner80/>\n\nThe Sheldon Chapel on the north side was added for the recusant Ralph Sheldon in about 1580.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> Its stone altar is said to be a gift from [[Pope Gregory XIII]].<ref name=Willis-Bund/> The church was restored in 1885 and the Sheldon Chapel was restored in 1891.<ref name=Willis-Bund/>\n\nThe tower has a [[Change ringing|ring]] of eight bells.<ref name=DoveDetails>{{cite web |url= http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?searchString=Beoley&Submit=+Go+&DoveID=BEOLEY |last1=Dawson |first1=George |last2=Pickford |first2=Chris |last3=Denton |first3=Philip |title=Beoley S Leonard |work=[[Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers]] |publisher=[[Central Council of Church Bell Ringers]] |date=3 December 2011 |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref> The oldest is the tenor bell, cast in 1601 by Hugh Watts<ref name=DoveDetails/> of [[Leicester]].<ref name=DoveFounders>{{cite web |url= http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/founders.php |title=Bell Founders |author=Dovemaster |work=[[Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers]] |publisher=[[Central Council of Church Bell Ringers]] |date=31 October 2012 |accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref> The seventh bell was cast in 1611 by one of the Newcombe family of [[Bellfounding|bellfounders]] of Leicester. The fourth bell was cast in 1622 by Henry III Oldfield<ref name=DoveDetails/> of Nottingham.<ref name=DoveFounders/> Richard Sanders of [[Bromsgrove]]<ref name=DoveFounders/> cast the third bell in 1708<ref name=DoveDetails/> and the fifth bell in 1709.<ref name=DoveDetails/> John [[Rudhall of Gloucester]]<ref name=DoveFounders/> cast the seventh bell in 1789<ref name=DoveDetails/> which completed a ring of six.<ref name=Willis-Bund/> In 1999 this was increased to eight by the addition of new treble and second bells cast by [[Whitechapel Bell Foundry]].<ref name=DoveDetails/>\n\n==Amenities==\nThe civil parish of Beoley has two public houses: the ''Cross and Bowling Green'' at Branson's Cross,  and the ''Village Inn'' at Holt End.<ref>[http://www.villageinnbeoley.co.uk/ The Village Inn, Beoley] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124015434/http://www.villageinnbeoley.co.uk/ |date=24 November 2011 }}</ref> The village has a first school<ref>[http://www.beoleyfirst.com/documents/welcome.php Beoley First School] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707223930/http://www.beoleyfirst.com/documents/welcome.php |date=7 July 2011 }}</ref> and a village hall.<ref>[http://www.beoley.org.uk/ Beoley Village Hall] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122111557/http://www.beoley.org.uk/ |date=22 January 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Edward Sheldon (translator)|Edward Sheldon]] (1599\u20131687), translator of religious works from French.\n*[[Ralph Sheldon]] (1623\u20131694), [[Cavalier|Royalist]] and [[antiquary]], nephew of Edward.\n*[[Mary Whateley]] (1738\u20131835), poet and playwright who wrote as Harriett Airy and Mary Darwall (her married name).\n*[[Sarah Cooper (marmalade maker)|Sarah Cooper]] (1848\u20131932), (''n\u00e9e'' Gill), originator of [[Frank Cooper's]] Oxford marmalade.\n*[[Sarah Falkland (journalist)|Sarah Falkland]] (living), a relief news presenter for [[BBC Midlands Today]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book |last=Pevsner |first=Nikolaus |authorlink=Nikolaus Pevsner |series=[[The Buildings of England]] |title=Worcestershire |year=1968 |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |location=Harmondsworth |pages=80\u201381 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Willis-Bund |editor1-first=J.W. |editor1-link=John William Willis-Bund |editor2-last=Page |editor2-first=W.H. |editor2-link=William Henry Page |series=[[Victoria County History]] |title=A History of the County of Worcester: Volume 4 |year=1924 |location=London |publisher= |pages=12\u201319 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Commons category|Beoley}}\n\n{{Bromsgrove}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Worcestershire]]\n[[Category:Villages in Worcestershire]]\n", "name_user": "AtticTapestry", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eParish church:Link toHugh Watts (bell-founder)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beoley"}
{"title_page": "Pinanga sylvestris", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|status = LC\n|status_system = IUCN3.1\n|status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn | author1 = Loftus, C. | author2 = Bachman, S. | lastauthoramp = yes | title = ''Pinanga sylvestris'' | page = e.T44393676A44431694 | year = 2013 | accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|genus = Pinanga\n|species = sylvestris\n|authority = ([[Jo\u00e3o de Loureiro|Lour.]]) Hodel, Palm J. 139: 55 (1998).<ref>{{cite web |title=Pinanga sylvestris |url=https://wcsp.science.kew.org/qsearch.do |website=World Checklist of Selected Plant Families (WCSP) |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens Kew/Science |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n|synonyms = *''Areca sylvestris'' Lour.\n*''Pinanga chinensis'' [[Odoardo Beccari|Becc.]]\n*''Pinanga cochinchinensis'' [[Carl Ludwig Blume|Blume]]\n*''Pinanga duperreana'' [[Jean Baptiste Louis Pierre|Pierre]] ex Becc.\n*''Pinanga macroclada'' [[Max Burret|Burret]]\n*''Ptychosperma cochinchinense'' (Blume) [[ Friedrich Anton Wilhelm Miquel|Miq.]]\n*''Ptychosperma sylvestris'' (Lour.) Miq. \n*''Seaforthia cochinchinensis'' (Blume) [[Carl Friedrich Philipp von Martius|Mart.]]\n*''Seaforthia sylvestris'' (Lour.) Blume ex Mart.\n}}\n\n'''''Pinanga sylvestris''''' is a species of tree in the [[Arecaceae]], or palm tree, family. It grows 2-6m tall, sometimes in bundles, shade tolerant, from [[Meghalaya]] (India) to [[Thailand]], [[Cambodia]], [[Vietnam]], [[Laos]] and [[China|Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3/China]].<ref name=IUCN/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Renuka |first1=C. |last2=Sreekumar |first2=V.B. |title=A Field Guide To The Palms Of India |date=2012 |publisher=Kerala Forest Research Institute |location=Peechi, Kerala |isbn=81-85041-74-1 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Sreekumar_Vb/publication/287890195_A_Field_guide_to_the_Palms_of_India/links/567a4f8508ae361c2f68d958.pdf |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=[[John Dransfield]] |last2=Barfod |first2=A.S. |last3=Pongsattayapipat |first3=R. |title=A preliminary checklist to Thai Palms |journal=Thai For. Bull. (Bot.) |date=2004 |volume=32 |page=32\u201372 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Anders_Barfod2/publication/256388501_A_preliminary_checklist_to_Thai_Palms/links/00b49522f06df71c22000000/A-preliminary-checklist-to-Thai-Palms.pdf |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"DyPhon\">{{cite book |last1=[[Pauline Dy Phon]] |title=Plants Used In Cambodia/Plantes utilis\u00e9es au Cambodge |date=2000 |publisher=Imprimerie Olympic |location=Phnom Penh|page=499-500|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=InD2RAAACAAJ}}</ref><ref name=\"haynes\" /><ref name=\"tordoff\">{{cite journal |last1=Tordoff |first1=Andrew W. |last2=Tran Hieu Minh |last3=Tran Quang Ngoc |title=A Feasibility Study for the Establishment of Ngoc Linh Nature Reserve, Quang Nam Province, Vietnam |journal=BirdLife International Vietnam Programme and the Forest Inventory and Planning Institute with financial support from the European Union, Conservation Report |date=2000 |volume=10 |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/bba4/b88d64d48b20d3787acec84536cb0976bb5b.pdf |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Pinanga sylvestris |url=http://apps.kew.org/herbcat/getHomePageResults.do?homePageSearchText=Pinanga+sylvestris |website=Herbarium Catalogue |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens Kew |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In Thailand it is recorded in the [[Khao Soi Dao Wildlife Sanctuary]], in [[Chanthaburi Province]], as a very common mid-storey tree in the ''[[Quercus semiserrata]]''-dominated rainforest at 1,400 to 1,540m.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Parnell |first1=J. |title=''Aeginetia flava'': a new and remarkable species of Aeginetia: Orobanchaceae from South-Eastern Thailand |journal=Kew Bulletin VOL. 67: 81Y84 (2012 |date=2012 |volume=67 |page=81-4 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/J_Parnell/publication/237062633_Aeginetia_flava_A_new_and_remarkable_species_of_Aeginetia_Orobanchaceae_from_South-Eastern_Thailand/links/0046351b1a3a5a5599000000.pdf |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>  In Cambodia it occurs uncommonly in coastal vegetation communities, but is common in dense and semi-dense evergreen rainforest in the lowlands and at moderate altitude.<ref name=\"DyPhon\" /><ref name=\"lewitz\">{{cite journal |last1=Lewitz |first1=S. |last2=Rollet |first2=B. |title=Lexique des noms d'arbres et d'arbustes du Cambodge |journal=Bulletin de l'\u00c9cole fran\u00e7aise d'Extr\u00eame-Orient |date=1973 |volume=60 |page=117-62 |url=https://www.persee.fr/doc/befeo_0336-1519_1973_num_60_1_5144 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>. The palm grows in similar dense and semi-dense communities in Laos and Vietnam.<ref name=\"DyPhon\" />. On the mountain of [[Ng\u1ecdc Linh]] in [[Qu\u1ea3ng Nam Province]] of Vietnam, it dominates the ground layer of low montane broadleaf evergreen forest, that occurs from 150 to 1000m.<ref name=\"tordoff\" />\n\nIn Cambodia, the palm is given the names ''sla snga:b'' (''sla''=palm/[[areca]], ''snga:b''=yawn, Lewitz & Rollet give it as ''sla sngap'', this sort grows in coastal forests), ''sla khmau'' (''khau''=black, Lewitz & Rollet give ''sla tourlieng'' as another name for this variety) and ''sla k\u00e2nnda\u00f4r'' (''k\u00e2nnda\u00f4r''=mouse, Haynes & McLaughlin give the name as ''sla condor'').<ref name=\"DyPhon\" /><ref name=\"haynes\">{{cite journal |last1=Haynes |first1=Jody |last2=McLaughlin |first2=John |title=Edible Palms and Their Uses |journal=University of Florida, Extension: Institute of Food and Agricultural Sciences, Fact Sheet |date=2000 |volume=MDCE-00-50-1 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Jody_Haynes/publication/242380543_Edible_Palms_and_Their_Uses_1/links/5553d63e08aeaaff3bf19dc7.pdf |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"lewitz\" /> The fruit of all of these Cambodian palms may replace [[Areca nut|areca nut]] in the [[Paan|betel]] quid, and sometimes the sla snga:b variety are used as bait in fishing, while the sla khmau and k\u00e2nnda\u00f4r types have their terminal bud and pith of the trunk harvested for food. In Zhongguo/China a common name is ''hua shan zhu'' ([[Pinyin]]).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Flora of China Editorial Committee |title=Flora of China (Acoraceae through Cyperaceae) |publisher=C. Y. Wu, P. H. Raven & D. Y. Hong (eds.) Fl. China. Science Press & Missouri Botanical Garden Press |location=Beijing & St. Louis |page=23: 1-515}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q15469436}}\n\n[[Category:Pinanga|sylvestris]]\n[[Category:Flora of Indo-China]]\n[[Category:Flora of China]]\n[[Category:Flora of Meghalaya]]\n\n\n{{palm-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|status = LC\n|status_system = IUCN3.1\n|status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn | author1 = Loftus, C. | author2 = Bachman, S. | lastauthoramp = yes | title = ''Pinanga sylvestris'' | page = e.T44393676A44431694 | year = 2013 | accessdate = 20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|genus = Pinanga\n|species = sylvestris\n|authority = ([[Jo\u00e3o de Loureiro|Lour.]]) Hodel, Palm J. 139: 55 (1998).<ref>{{cite web |title=Pinanga sylvestris |url=https://wcsp.science.kew.org/qsearch.do |website=World Checklist of Selected Plant Families (WCSP) |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens Kew/Science |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n|synonyms = *''Areca sylvestris'' Lour.\n*''Pinanga chinensis'' [[Odoardo Beccari|Becc.]]\n*''Pinanga cochinchinensis'' [[Carl Ludwig Blume|Blume]]\n*''Pinanga duperreana'' [[Jean Baptiste Louis Pierre|Pierre]] ex Becc.\n*''Pinanga macroclada'' [[Max Burret|Burret]]\n*''Ptychosperma cochinchinense'' (Blume) [[ Friedrich Anton Wilhelm Miquel|Miq.]]\n*''Ptychosperma sylvestris'' (Lour.) Miq. \n*''Seaforthia cochinchinensis'' (Blume) [[Carl Friedrich Philipp von Martius|Mart.]]\n*''Seaforthia sylvestris'' (Lour.) Blume ex Mart.\n}}\n\n'''''Pinanga sylvestris''''' is a species of tree in the [[Arecaceae]], or palm tree, family. It grows 2-6m tall, sometimes in bundles, shade tolerant, from [[Meghalaya]] (India) to Thailand, Cambodia, Vietnam, Laos and China.<ref name=IUCN/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Renuka |first1=C. |last2=Sreekumar |first2=V.B. |title=A Field Guide To The Palms Of India |date=2012 |publisher=Kerala Forest Research Institute |location=Peechi, Kerala |isbn=81-85041-74-1 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Sreekumar_Vb/publication/287890195_A_Field_guide_to_the_Palms_of_India/links/567a4f8508ae361c2f68d958.pdf |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=[[John Dransfield]] |last2=Barfod |first2=A.S. |last3=Pongsattayapipat |first3=R. |title=A preliminary checklist to Thai Palms |journal=Thai For. Bull. (Bot.) |date=2004 |volume=32 |page=32\u201372 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Anders_Barfod2/publication/256388501_A_preliminary_checklist_to_Thai_Palms/links/00b49522f06df71c22000000/A-preliminary-checklist-to-Thai-Palms.pdf |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"DyPhon\">{{cite book |last1=[[Pauline Dy Phon]] |title=Plants Used In Cambodia/Plantes utilis\u00e9es au Cambodge |date=2000 |publisher=Imprimerie Olympic |location=Phnom Penh|page=499-500|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=InD2RAAACAAJ}}</ref><ref name=\"haynes\" /><ref name=\"tordoff\">{{cite journal |last1=Tordoff |first1=Andrew W. |last2=Tran Hieu Minh |last3=Tran Quang Ngoc |title=A Feasibility Study for the Establishment of Ngoc Linh Nature Reserve, Quang Nam Province, Vietnam |journal=BirdLife International Vietnam Programme and the Forest Inventory and Planning Institute with financial support from the European Union, Conservation Report |date=2000 |volume=10 |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/bba4/b88d64d48b20d3787acec84536cb0976bb5b.pdf |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Pinanga sylvestris |url=http://apps.kew.org/herbcat/getHomePageResults.do?homePageSearchText=Pinanga+sylvestris |website=Herbarium Catalogue |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens Kew |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> In Thailand it is recorded in the [[Khao Soi Dao Wildlife Sanctuary]], in [[Chanthaburi Province]], as a very common mid-storey tree in the ''[[Quercus semiserrata]]''-dominated rainforest at 1,400 to 1,540m.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Parnell |first1=J. |title=''Aeginetia flava'': a new and remarkable species of Aeginetia: Orobanchaceae from South-Eastern Thailand |journal=Kew Bulletin VOL. 67: 81Y84 (2012 |date=2012 |volume=67 |page=81-4 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/J_Parnell/publication/237062633_Aeginetia_flava_A_new_and_remarkable_species_of_Aeginetia_Orobanchaceae_from_South-Eastern_Thailand/links/0046351b1a3a5a5599000000.pdf |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>  In Cambodia it occurs uncommonly in coastal vegetation communities, but is common in dense and semi-dense evergreen rainforest in the lowlands and at moderate altitude.<ref name=\"DyPhon\" /><ref name=\"lewitz\">{{cite journal |last1=Lewitz |first1=S. |last2=Rollet |first2=B. |title=Lexique des noms d'arbres et d'arbustes du Cambodge |journal=Bulletin de l'\u00c9cole fran\u00e7aise d'Extr\u00eame-Orient |date=1973 |volume=60 |page=117-62 |url=https://www.persee.fr/doc/befeo_0336-1519_1973_num_60_1_5144 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>. The palm grows in similar dense and semi-dense communities in Laos and Vietnam.<ref name=\"DyPhon\" />. On the mountain of [[Ng\u1ecdc Linh]] in [[Qu\u1ea3ng Nam Province]] of Vietnam, it dominates the ground layer of low montane broadleaf evergreen forest, that occurs from 150 to 1000m.<ref name=\"tordoff\" />\n\nIn Cambodia, the palm is given the names ''sla snga:b'' (''sla''=palm/[[areca]], ''snga:b''=yawn, Lewitz & Rollet give it as ''sla sngap'', this sort grows in coastal forests), ''sla khmau'' (''khau''=black, Lewitz & Rollet give ''sla tourlieng'' as another name for this variety) and ''sla k\u00e2nnda\u00f4r'' (''k\u00e2nnda\u00f4r''=mouse, Haynes & McLaughlin give the name as ''sla condor'').<ref name=\"DyPhon\" /><ref name=\"haynes\">{{cite journal |last1=Haynes |first1=Jody |last2=McLaughlin |first2=John |title=Edible Palms and Their Uses |journal=University of Florida, Extension: Institute of Food and Agricultural Sciences, Fact Sheet |date=2000 |volume=MDCE-00-50-1 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Jody_Haynes/publication/242380543_Edible_Palms_and_Their_Uses_1/links/5553d63e08aeaaff3bf19dc7.pdf |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"lewitz\" /> The fruit of all of these Cambodian palms may replace [[Areca nut|areca nut]] in the [[Paan|betel]] quid, and sometimes the sla snga:b variety are used as bait in fishing, while the sla khmau and k\u00e2nnda\u00f4r types have their terminal bud and pith of the trunk harvested for food. In Zhongguo/China a common name is ''hua shan zhu'' ([[Pinyin]]).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Flora of China Editorial Committee |title=Flora of China (Acoraceae through Cyperaceae) |publisher=C. Y. Wu, P. H. Raven & D. Y. Hong (eds.) Fl. China. Science Press & Missouri Botanical Garden Press |location=Beijing & St. Louis |page=23: 1-515}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q15469436}}\n\n[[Category:Pinanga|sylvestris]]\n[[Category:Flora of Indo-China]]\n[[Category:Flora of China]]\n[[Category:Flora of Meghalaya]]\n\n\n{{palm-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Brunswicknic", "label": "safe", "comment": "Not everybody is good with world geography, I respect a nation's name for itself", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pinanga_sylvestris"}
{"title_page": "Central University of Technology", "text_new": "{{short description|University in Bloemfontein, South Africa}}\n{{Infobox University\n|name            = Central University of Technology, Free State\n|image           = Central University of Technology logo.svg\n|image_upright   = 0.9\n|motto           = Thinking Beyond\n|established     = 1981\n|type            = [[Public university|Public]] [[University of Technology]]\n|staff           = 1 100\n|chancellor      = Madam Justice Mahube Molemela\n|vice_chancellor = Prof. Henk de Jager\n|students        = 20 000\n|city            = [[Bloemfontein]], [[Welkom]]\n|state           = [[Free State (South African province)|Free State]]\n|country         = South Africa\n|colours         = Red, yellow and blue <br> {{color box|#A60E13}} {{color box|#FFCA05}} {{color box|#00457C}}\n|website         = {{url|https://www.cut.ac.za/}}\n}}\n'''Central University of Technology, Free State''' or '''CUT''' is a [[University of Technology]] in [[Bloemfontein]] in the [[Free State (South African province)|Free State]] province of South Africa. It was established in 1981 as \"[[Technikon]] Free State\". As part of the South African government's restructuring of tertiary education for the new millennium it was promoted to university of technology status.\n==About CUT==\nThe university (then still known as the \u201cTechnikon Free State\u201d) opened its doors in 1981, with 285 students enrolled in mainly secretarial, art and design programmes.  Today, the institution boasts more than 21 000 students who have decided to make CUT their academic partner in earning a qualification and gaining appropriate work-integrated learning to equip and prepare them for professional practice. With the restructuring of the higher education landscape in 2004, CUT embraced its new status as a university of technology (UoT), positioning itself to succeed as such.   The qualifications on offer reside in four faculties, namely Faculty of Health and Environmental Sciences; Faculty of Humanities; Faculty of Engineering, Built Environment and Information Technology (IT); and Faculty of Management Sciences.  The university offers certificates and diplomas at undergraduate level, as well as advanced diplomas, postgraduate diplomas at honours level, and master\u2019s and doctoral degrees in order to increase the production of world-class postgraduate programmes and high-quality outputs for research.\n\nCUT\u2019s vision is to be \u201can engaged university that focuses on producing quality social and technological innovations for socio-economic development, primarily in the Central region of South Africa\u201d. This vision has four pillars, namely planning, products, people and pennies, each describing an important aspect of the university\u2019s future. It does not come as a surprise, then, that Management, staff and students have formulated a strategic vision for the future that is all about heart. They call it the\n\u201cVision 2020 Statement\u201d, and within it are ideas and goals that are supported and inspired by the university across all platforms and programmes. It represents the university\u2019s aspirations and determination as a UoT, and has allowed the university to contribute substantively to addressing the developmental needs of the Free State, the Central region, South Africa and the continent.\n\nThe university\u2019s goal is to be a leader in areas of social and technological innovations and research. CUT believes that no successful geographical region has ever established a technology-based industry without a leading educational institution in its midst, and the university wants to become this institution. In this lies the strength of the planning pillar, which outlines the step-by-step implementation and review of the main practices and outcomes of Vision 2020.\n\n===Campuses===\nCUT is the foremost higher education institution in the heartland of South Africa. The university has two campuses \u2013 one in Bloemfontein, the judicial capital of South Africa, and one in Welkom, in the heart of the Free State goldfields. The two campuses offer education opportunities in a number of technological fields, including science, technology, engineering and mathematics (STEM); management sciences; humanities; and education.<ref name=\"auto\">https://www.cut.ac.za/cut-at-a-glance</ref>\n\n===Faculties===\n* [https://www.cut.ac.za/faculty/faculty-of-engineering-information-technology Faculty of Engineering, Built Environment and Information Technology]\n* [https://www.cut.ac.za/faculty/health-and-environmental-sciences Faculty of Health and Environmental Sciences]\n* [https://www.cut.ac.za/faculty/humanities Faculty of Humanities]\n* [https://www.cut.ac.za/faculty/management-sciences Faculty of Management Sciences]\n\n===Language Policy===\nTeaching and Learning facilitation at CUT in all learning environments, such as the classroom, laboratories, etc. will be conducted in English.\n<ref name=\"auto\">https://www.cut.ac.za/policies-and-forms</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{South African universities}} {{FNB Varsity Cup}} \n\n{{coord|29|07|17|S|26|12|49|E|region:ZA-FS_type:landmark_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Central University Of Technology}}\n[[Category:Public universities in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Universities in the Free State (province)]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1981]]\n\n{{SouthAfrica-university-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|University in Bloemfontein, South Africa}}\n{{Infobox University\n|name            = Central University of Technology, Free State\n|image           = Central University of Technology logo.svg\n|image_upright   = 0.9\n|motto           = Thinking Beyond\n|established     = 1981\n|type            = [[Public university|Public]] [[University of Technology]]\n|staff           = 1 100\n|chancellor      = Madam Justice Mahube Molemela\n|vice_chancellor = Prof. Henk de Jager\n|students        = 20 000\n|city            = [[Bloemfontein]], [[Welkom]]\n|state           = [[Free State (South African province)|Free State]]\n|country         = South Africa\n|colours         = Red, yellow and blue <br> {{color box|#A60E13}} {{color box|#FFCA05}} {{color box|#00457C}}\n|website         = {{url|https://www.cut.ac.za/}}\n}}\n'''Central University of Technology, Free State''' or '''CUT''' is a [[University of Technology]] in [[Bloemfontein]] in the [[Free State (South African province)|Free State]] province of South Africa. It was established in 1981 as \"[[Technikon]] Free State\". As part of the South African government's restructuring of tertiary education for the new millennium it was promoted to university of technology status.\n==About CUT==\nThe university (then still known as the \u201cTechnikon Free State\u201d) opened its doors in 1981, with 285 students enrolled in mainly secretarial, art and design programmes.  Today, the institution boasts more than 21 000 students who have decided to make CUT their academic partner in earning a qualification and gaining appropriate work-integrated learning to equip and prepare them for professional practice. With the restructuring of the higher education landscape in 2004, CUT embraced its new status as a university of technology (UoT), positioning itself to succeed as such.   The qualifications on offer reside in four faculties, namely Faculty of Health and Environmental Sciences; Faculty of Humanities; Faculty of Engineering, Built Environment and Information Technology (IT); and Faculty of Management Sciences.  The university offers certificates and diplomas at undergraduate level, as well as advanced diplomas, postgraduate diplomas at honours level, and master\u2019s and doctoral degrees in order to increase the production of world-class postgraduate programmes and high-quality outputs for research.\n\nCUT\u2019s vision is to be \u201can engaged university that focuses on producing quality social and technological innovations for socio-economic development, primarily in the Central region of South Africa\u201d. This vision has four pillars, namely planning, products, people and pennies, each describing an important aspect of the university\u2019s future. It does not come as a surprise, then, that Management, staff and students have formulated a strategic vision for the future that is all about heart. They call it the\n\u201cVision 2020 Statement\u201d, and within it are ideas and goals that are supported and inspired by the university across all platforms and programmes. It represents the university\u2019s aspirations and determination as a UoT, and has allowed the university to contribute substantively to addressing the developmental needs of the Free State, the Central region, South Africa and the continent.\n\nThe university\u2019s goal is to be a leader in areas of social and technological innovations and research. CUT believes that no successful geographical region has ever established a technology-based industry without a leading educational institution in its midst, and the university wants to become this institution. In this lies the strength of the planning pillar, which outlines the step-by-step implementation and review of the main practices and outcomes of Vision 2020.\n\n===Campuses===\nCUT is the foremost higher education institution in the heartland of South Africa. The university has two campuses \u2013 one in Bloemfontein, the judicial capital of South Africa, and one in Welkom, in the heart of the Free State goldfields. The two campuses offer education opportunities in a number of technological fields, including science, technology, engineering and mathematics (STEM); management sciences; humanities; and education.<ref name=\"auto\">https://www.cut.ac.za/cut-at-a-glance</ref>\n\n===Faculties===\n* [https://www.cut.ac.za/faculty/faculty-of-engineering-information-technology Faculty of Engineering, Built Environment and Information Technology]\n* [https://www.cut.ac.za/faculty/health-and-environmental-sciences Faculty of Health and Environmental Sciences]\n* [https://www.cut.ac.za/faculty/humanities Faculty of Humanities]\n* [https://www.cut.ac.za/faculty/management-sciences Faculty of Management Sciences]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{South African universities}} {{FNB Varsity Cup}} \n\n{{coord|29|07|17|S|26|12|49|E|region:ZA-FS_type:landmark_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Central University Of Technology}}\n[[Category:Public universities in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Universities in the Free State (province)]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1981]]\n\n{{SouthAfrica-university-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Leandra.jordaan", "label": "safe", "comment": "/*Language Policy/ Added section to page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_University_of_Technology"}
{"title_page": "TCEC Season 17", "text_new": "The 17th season of the [[Top Chess Engine Championship]] began on 2 January 2020. The defending champion is [[Stockfish (chess)|Stockfish]], which defeated [[AllieStein]] in the [[TCEC Season 16]] superfinal.\n\nSeason 17 featured for the first time two separate leagues, one for [[GPU]]-based engines and one for [[CPU]]-based engines. TCEC also doubled the computing power available to CPU engines, from 44 cores to 88.\n\n==Overview==\nIn keeping with its identity as a competition run at long time controls on high-end hardware,<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.chessblog.com/2013/08/tcec-computer-chess-championship-new.html|title = TCEC Computer Chess Championship New Season starts August 26th|last = Kosteniuk |first = Alexandra|date = August 15, 2013|website = Chess News Blog|accessdate = October 25, 2013|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131025063745/http://www.chessblog.com/2013/08/tcec-computer-chess-championship-new.html|archivedate = October 25, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = https://nypost.com/2013/06/09/engine-super-bowl/|title = Engine Super Bowl|last = Soltis|first = Andy|date = June 9, 2013|website = New York Post|accessdate = October 25, 2013}}</ref> TCEC secured a hardware upgrade for the competing CPU engines.<ref name=\"S17Info\">{{citeweb|url=http://www.chessdom.com/tcec-s17-detailed-information/|title=TCEC S17 \u2013 detailed information|publisher=Chessdom|date=21 December 2019}}</ref> Among other changes, the number of cores available is doubled from 44 to 88, the operating system used is now [[Linux]], and Syzygy [[endgame tablebases]] are now cached directly in the RAM for faster access. Because this upgrade advantages CPU engines compared to GPU engines, TCEC split the qualification paths to Premier Division by introducing separate leagues for CPU and GPU engines. While an upgrade to the GPU servers is being secured, the CPU leagues are played first.\n\n===Structure===\nFor CPU engines, there will first be a Qualification League consisting of 16 engines, followed by League 2 (16 engines) and League 1 (16 engines). In the Qualification League the top 6 engines promote. In League 2 the top 4 engines promote. The engines in each league are seeded based on their performances in previous seasons. For GPU engines, there will be one league only, with up to 16 competitors. The top 2 GPU engines will then contest a playoff against the top 4 CPU engines in League 1, with the four highest-placing engines promoting to Premier Division.\n\nPremier Division is also expanded from 8 engines to 10. Six engines - [[Stockfish (chess)|Stockfish]], [[Komodo (chess)|Komodo]], [[Houdini (chess)|Houdini]], [[Leela Chess Zero]], [[AllieStein]], and Stoofvlees - are seeded directly to Premier Division, based on their top 6 finishes in the previous season. Finally, the top two engines in Premier Division qualify for the 100-game superfinal match.\n\n==Results==\n===CPU Qualification League===\nAfter not competing for five seasons, Season 11 Div 3 engine Defenchess trailblazed the qualification league. It scored 18 wins while conceding no losses, finishing 3.5 points clear at the top. It was the only undefeated engine. Demolito and Winter also locked up two of the promotion spots smoothly, but the remaining three slots were closely contested. Among the competitors Igel was the only engine to not lose to Defenchess and Demolito, but it lost to bottom-half engines FabChess and Topple. Comparatively, iCE was whitewashed by Defenchess and Igel, but it turned in a strong performance against its other rivals, losing only one other game to Winter. Pirarucu went through a tense moment when it lost to Winter in the penultimate round; however it pulled out a win with Black against Topple to promote. 7th-placed Minic was in a promotion spot all the way up to the final round, when it lost to Gogobello while iCE beat Counter. This left the two tied at 17.5 points. Minic had the better [[Sonneborn\u2013Berger score]], but it also had one crash, and the number of crashes was the first tiebreak. Nonetheless, in a stroke of good fortune for Minic (and 8th-placed PeSTO), the League Two engines chess22k and [[Fritz (chess)|Fritz]] crashed three times during testing for the division. By TCEC rules, if this happened, the author(s) would have to update the engine or it is disqualified. chess22k's and Fritz's authors were not able to update the engines in time, resulting in Minic and PeSTO promoting as lucky losers.<ref>https://imgur.com/GHNF1Zu</ref>\n\n{{#invoke:Sports table|main|style=WDL\n\n|show_matches=false\n|update=complete\n\n|source=[https://www.tcec-chess.com/archive.html?season=17&div=ql&game=1]\n|for_against_style=none\n|res_col_header=Q\n|result1=WC \n|result2=WC \n|result3=WC \n|result4=WC \n|result5=WC \n|result6=WC \n|col_WC=green1 |text_WC={{nowrap|Advance to League Two}}\n|result7=WB \n|result8=WB \n|col_WB=blue1 |text_WB={{nowrap|Advance to League Two (see text)}}\n|team1=DEF|team2=DEM|team3=WIN|team4=PIR|team5=IGE|team6=ICE|team7=MIN|team8=PES|team9=MAR|team10=GOG|team11=TOP|team12=COU|team13=FAB|team14=TUC|team15=ASY|team16=CHE|\n\n|win_DEF=18 |draw_DEF=12 |loss_DEF=0\n|win_DEM=12 |draw_DEM=17 |loss_DEM=1\n|win_WIN=14 |draw_WIN=12 |loss_WIN=4\n|win_PIR=10 |draw_PIR=16 |loss_PIR=4\n|win_IGE=10 |draw_IGE=16 |loss_IGE=4\n|win_ICE=10 |draw_ICE=15 |loss_ICE=5\n|win_MIN=10 |draw_MIN=15 |loss_MIN=5\n|win_PES=8 |draw_PES=17 |loss_PES=5\n|win_MAR=8 |draw_MAR=16 |loss_MAR=6\n|win_GOG=8 |draw_GOG=14 |loss_GOG=8\n|win_TOP=8 |draw_TOP=12 |loss_TOP=10\n|win_COU=4 |draw_COU=12 |loss_COU=14\n|win_FAB=3 |draw_FAB=14 |loss_FAB=13\n|win_TUC=4 |draw_TUC=9 |loss_TUC=17\n|win_ASY=2 |draw_ASY=13 |loss_ASY=15\n|win_CHE=2 |draw_CHE=8 |loss_CHE=20\n\n|winpoints=1\n|drawpoints=0.5\n|losspoints=0\n\n|team_header=Engine\n|name_DEF=Defenchess |short_DEF=DEF\n|name_DEM=Demolito |short_DEM=DEM\n|name_WIN=Winter |short_WIN=WIN\n|name_PIR=Pirarucu |short_PIR=PIR\n|name_IGE=Igel |short_IGE=IGE\n|name_ICE=iCE |short_ICE=ICE\n|name_MIN=Minic |short_MIN=MIN\n|name_PES=PeSTO |short_PES=PES\n|name_MAR=Marvin |short_MAR=MAR\n|name_GOG=Gogobello |short_GOG=GOG\n|name_TOP=Topple |short_TOP=TOP\n|name_COU=Counter |short_COU=COU\n|name_FAB=FabChess |short_FAB=FAB\n|name_TUC=Tucano |short_TUC=TUC\n|name_ASY=Asymptote |short_ASY=ASY\n|name_CHE=Cheese |short_CHE=CHE\n\n}}\n\n===CPU League Two===\nFormer Premier Division engine Fire won League Two. It had been relegated in [[TCEC Season 16|the previous season]] because its developer had submitted a drastically different neural network-based version that turned out to be significantly weaker. This season, the original, traditional engine played, and it dominated with an undefeated 22/28 (16 wins and 12 draws). It defeated seven engines, including fourth-place Vajolet, 2-0. Second placed Defenchess also turned in a strong performance, finishing with an undefeated 20.5/28 (13 wins and 15 draws). For the other promoted engines, Winter and PeSTO performed surprisingly well, comfortably finishing above their peers in 7th and 8th respectively. The remaining five promoted engines occupied the bottom five spots, and were all relegated along with Wasp (which crashed three times).\n\nAfter the division concluded, in a repeat of testing for League Two, four League One engines either pulled out or did not run on the new Linux operating system, resulting in the 5th-8th placed engines in League One promoting.\n\n{{#invoke:Sports table|main|style=WDL\n\n|show_matches=false\n|update=complete\n\n|source=[https://www.tcec-chess.com/archive.html?season=17&div=l1&game=1], see also [https://tcecbayeselo.chessdom.org/2020/01/25/tcec-season-17-league2-game-240-defenchess-2-3_dev-igel-2-3-1/] for table with Wasp's score zeroed out\n|for_against_style=none\n|res_col_header=Q\n|result1=WC \n|result2=WC \n|result3=WC \n|result4=WC \n|col_WC=green1 |text_WC={{nowrap|Advance to League One}}\n|result5=WB\n|result6=WB\n|result7=WB\n|result8=WB\n|col_WB=blue1|text_WB={{nowrap|Advance to League One (see text)}}\n|team1=FIR|team2=DEF|team3=RUB|team4=VAJ|team5=PED|team6=NEM|team7=WIN|team8=PES|team9=GUL|team10=WAS|team11=TEX|team12=DEM|team13=MIN|team14=ICE|team15=IGE|team16=PIR|\n\n|win_FIR=16|draw_FIR=14 |loss_FIR=0\n|win_DEF=14|draw_DEF=16|loss_DEF=0\n|win_RUB=9 |draw_RUB=19|loss_RUB=2\n|win_VAJ=10 |draw_VAJ=15 |loss_VAJ=5\n|win_PED=7|draw_PED=19 |loss_PED=4\n|win_WIN=6|draw_WIN=18|loss_WIN=6\n|win_PES=6|draw_PES=17|loss_PES=7\n|win_NEM=7 |draw_NEM=15|loss_NEM=8\n|win_GUL=4 |draw_GUL=21 |loss_GUL=5\n|win_WAS=5 |draw_WAS=19 |loss_WAS=6 |status_WAS=D\n|win_DEM=7 |draw_DEM=13 |loss_DEM=10\n|win_TEX=4 |draw_TEX=19 |loss_TEX=7\n|win_MIN=3 |draw_MIN=19 |loss_MIN=8\n|win_ICE=1 |draw_ICE=20 |loss_ICE=9\n|win_IGE=3 |draw_IGE=15 |loss_IGE=12\n|win_PIR=3 |draw_PIR=11 |loss_PIR=16\n\n|winpoints=1\n|drawpoints=0.5\n|losspoints=0\n\n|team_header=Engine\n|name_DEF=Defenchess |short_DEF=DEF\n|name_DEM=Demolito |short_DEM=DEM\n|name_WIN=Winter |short_WIN=WIN\n|name_PIR=Pirarucu |short_PIR=PIR\n|name_IGE=Igel |short_IGE=IGE\n|name_ICE=iCE |short_ICE=ICE\n|name_MIN=Minic |short_MIN=MIN\n|name_PES=PeSTO |short_PES=PES\n|name_FIR=Fire|short_FIR=FIR\n|name_TEX=Texel|short_TEX=TEX\n|name_RUB=RubiChess|short_RUB=RUBP\n|name_NEM=Nemorino|short_NEM=NEM\n|name_GUL=Gull|short_GUL=GUL\n|name_PED=Pedone|short_PED=PED\n|name_WAS=Wasp|short_WAS=WAS\n|name_VAJ=Vajolet|short_VAJ=VAJ\n\n}}\n\n===CPU League One===\nDuring testing for League One, three engines (Booot, Chiron, and ChessBrainVB) did not play because they did not run on [[Wine (software)|Wine]], the [[compatibility layer]] that TCEC is using to run Windows programs on Linux. One further engine (former champion [[Jonny]]) crashed and was not updated in time. As a result, the 5th to 8th-placed engines from League Two, Pedone, Nemorino, Winter and PeSTO, promoted as lucky losers.\n\nIn League One itself, Xiphos, which had just missed out on promotion in Season 16, vaulted to an early lead after scoring five wins with no losses. However, after this bright start, it failed to score more wins. This allowed former Division Premier engine Ethereal to seize first place, in spite of a loss to Komodo MCTS. Fellow competitors Fire and Komodo MCTS also amassed more wins than Xiphos, and by the midway point had overtaken it in the standings. By the final double round robin, Ethereal, Fire and Komodo MCTS had more or less secured a playoff spot. Xiphos, who had yet to lose, was barely holding on to fourth place, with rofChade and Defenchess both breathing down its neck. When it lost a crucial game to Fire, it allowed rofChade to pull even, with Defenchess half a point further back. Xiphos knocked Defenchess out of contention with a head-to-head win, but with rofChade having the superior tiebreaks (by number of wins), it needed to either hope for Fire to beat rofChade or to beat Vajolet in its last game. When both games ended drawn, Xiphos finished fifth, again just missing out on promotion.\n\nFor the other engines, Laser, which had pipped Xiphos to a playoff spot last season, was able to remain unbeaten until the final double round robin. However, it collapsed in that round, losing three games (plus forfeited a fourth due to a crash). Winter scored likely the biggest upset of the league by defeating rofChade once, but the rest of the division was not kind to it and fellow lucky losers Nemorino and PeSTO, with all three engines placing in the bottom four. Former Division Premier engine Fizbo, which had been forced to run at a much slower speed because it was not able to utilize all the hardware available to it, finished solidly last, five points off the pace. \n\n{{#invoke:Sports table|main|style=WDL\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|show_matches=false\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|update=complete\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|source=[https://www.tcec-chess.com/archive.html?season=17&div=cpul1&game=1]\t\t\t\t\t\t\